         <abstract>
            <p>A recent theorem of Zhang asserts that H(α) + H(1 - α) ≥ C for all algebraic numbers &lt;tex-math&gt;$\alpha \neq 0, 1, (1 \pm \sqrt{-3})/2$&lt;/tex-math&gt;, and some constant &lt;latex&gt;$C &gt; 0$&lt;/latex&gt;. An elementary proof of this, with a sharp value for the constant, is given (the optimal value of C is &lt;tex-math&gt;$\frac{1}{2} \log(\frac{1}{2}(1 + \sqrt 5)) = 0, 2406 \cdots$&lt;/tex-math&gt;, attained for eight values of α) and generalizations to other curves are discussed.</p>
          </abstract>
